Thomas:

This may be a case of mistaken intent -- I don&#39;t believe that 
&quot;assertEquals&quot; was intended to &quot;test&quot; the validity of an &quot;equals()&quot; 
implementation, but rather to simply test if two objects/primitives/etc... 
are equal.   Like testing that the result of an operation is equal to the 
expected result.

I seem to remember someone submitting a set of assert methods that can be 
used to verify an &quot;equals&quot; implementation.

When I&#39;ve implemented equals/hashcode/compareTo I&#39;ve hand coded the tests 
(ok, I do some cut & paste, too).

         Ken

At 05:10 AM 5/20/2003, you wrote:

&gt;Fine but I really feel equals should behave so.
&gt;The question is more do you have a need for NON-commutative equals.
&gt;
&gt;As the testing of the equality&#39;s implementation is better done by :
&gt;
&gt;   [code]
&gt;      testAequalsBimplementation ()
&gt;      {
&gt;        assertTrue (&quot;A is not equal to B&quot;,  a.equals (b));
&gt;      }
&gt;      testBequalsAimplementation ()
&gt;      {
&gt;        assertTrue (&quot;B is not equal to A&quot;,  b.equals (a));
&gt;      }
&gt;   [/code]
&gt;
&gt;The REAL / FULL equality is therefore better evaluated by either the
&gt;combination of both... and that&#39;s precisely what the assertEquals
&gt;should test IMHO !
&gt;
&gt;Equality is really equivalent to test both cases :
&gt;   [code]
&gt;      testAequalsB ()
&gt;      {
&gt;        assertEquals (&quot;A is not equals to B&quot;, a, b);
&gt;      }
&gt;   [/code]
&gt;
&gt;but I believe many people don&#39;t have the need to have equals() being
&gt;implemented too extensively & therefore are pleased with most failure
&gt;returned to have an acceptable implemetation.
